A. Against “Our reply” under Sufficiency of Disclosure u/s 10(4)

The current reply is broadly fine, but I suggest adding more direct references from the specification and figures. The reply should show that the specification already discloses the input-process-output pipeline and is not merely result-oriented.

Suggested addition/modification under this “Our reply”:

Please consider adding that the specification provides implementation details at multiple places:

1. Paragraph [0030] describes the core invention: the personalized/contextual shadow is generated based on the user’s social-media profile and/or virtual-environment-related parameters, and is rendered in view of the shadow attributes of the actual base shadow.

2. Paragraph [0031] explains the technical/user effect of the personalized/contextual shadow: enhancing user interest in the virtual environment, providing an additional communication modality, and enabling advertisement/promotion.

3. Paragraphs [0032]–[0034] and Figure 1 explain the avatar 104, base shadow 106, profile picture/context 108, and personalized shadow 110. Figure 1 visually shows the base shadow being transfigured into the personalized shadow. This can help address the objection that “personalized shadow” is ambiguous.

4. Paragraphs [0035]–[0040] and Figure 2 disclose system 200 including processor/controller 202, I/O interface 204, modules 206, transceiver 208, memory 210, database 212, and operating system 214. This supports that the invention is implemented through a technical system and is not just an abstract idea.

5. Paragraph [0041] directly supports extraction of user/media content. It discloses media content such as images, videos, text, emoticons, and user logs, including profile photos/videos, liked/commented media, user-uploaded comments/status/text, emoticons used in likes/comments/chats, and user-accessed page/account information.

6. Paragraph [0042] supports extraction of virtual-environment parameters, including avatar location, avatar action, avatar emotion, avatar field of view, user interaction profile, and engagement time.

7. Paragraph [0043] supports contextual image/vector generation. It discloses generating a contextual image, generating contextual vectors based on media content/environment parameters, assigning priority based on user interest, determining interest level from user interaction, likes/dislikes, probabilistic calculations in vector space, similarity search, vector grouping, identifying the highest-priority contextual vector, and generating the contextual image based on that vector.

8. Paragraph [0044] supports determining a base shadow and shadow attributes, including orientation and dimension.

9. Paragraph [0045] supports transforming the contextual image based on shadow attributes to generate the personalized shadow, mapping/rendering the personalized shadow with the avatar, and modifying the personalized shadow based on user activity or environmental condition.

10. Paragraphs [0051]–[0057] and Figure 3 provide a detailed process flow. They disclose extraction of media content/environment parameters at block 302a, use of a social-media crawler, like/dislike categorization, image captioning at block 302b, CNN/RNN-based captioning, word embedding at block 302c, Word2Vec/GloVe, similarity search at block 304a, mapping vectors to contexts such as party/gaming/shopping/travel/music/solitude/brand, priority assignment at block 304b, and avatar positioning / dynamic base-shadow generation at block 306a.

11. Figure 3 shows the complete technical flow: social feed crawler, image/text input, likes/dislikes, comments, image caption generator, embeddings, similarity search, prioritized context vector/text, GAN model for context/text-to-image generation, contextual images, conditional masking, rendering orientation/dimensions, shadow generation, avatar positioning, shadow-attribute extraction, spatial vector generation, TSGAN generator/discriminator, conditional vector, and transfigured shadow.

12. Figure 4 shows the implementation modules: social media crawler module 404, virtual-environment-related parameters 406, contextual vector generation module 408, shadow generator and attribute extractor module 410, contextual image generation and processing module 412, shadow transfiguration module 414, and database/memory 416 storing user image metadata, image captions, user text data, context vectors, shadow attributes, contextual image, processed image, and transfigured images.

13. Figure 5 supports contextual-image processing: contextual image 502, conditional mask 504, orientation 506, dimension 508, and avatar/shadow rendering 510.

14. Figure 6 supports transfigured-shadow generation: contextual image, masking, shadow/color, shadow attributes, orientation/dimension adaptation, render image, generator/discriminator, noise vector, TSGAN, and generated transfigured image.

15. Figure 12 maps directly to the claimed method steps 1202, 1204, 1206, and 1208.

My technical point to be added:
The disclosure is not just saying “generate a personalized shadow.” It describes the full pipeline:

media/social data + virtual-environment parameters → contextual vectors/contextual image → base shadow + shadow attributes → masking/orientation/dimension adaptation → personalized/transfigured shadow rendered with avatar.

Also, instead of only saying GAN/CNN/NLP are known, please clarify that the invention is not claiming a new CNN/GAN/NLP model itself. The invention is the specific integration of these known components into the above personalized-shadow generation pipeline.

